<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between a wine cellar and a wine cooler?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A wine cooler is a self-contained appliance — typically 12 to 200 bottles — that plugs into an outlet. A wine cellar is a dedicated conditioned room or walk-in enclosure, usually 500 to 5,000+ bottles, built with an insulated envelope, a 6-mil poly vapor barrier, and serviced by an HVAC-grade refrigeration unit that includes active humidity control. The equipment lives outside the cellar on a ducted or split system, while a coil or evaporator sits inside. Cellars are a building system — cooler, humidity, vapor barrier, and envelope all working together — not a plug-in appliance."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does humidity control matter in a wine cellar?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Wine cellars target 50–70% relative humidity. Below 50% RH, corks dry out and shrink, air enters the bottle, and the wine oxidizes — expensive bottles are ruined silently, sometimes over years. Labels dry, peel, and lose value for collectors. Above 70% RH, mold grows on labels, racks, and ceilings. A residential refrigeration unit without humidity control — essentially a window AC — will dehumidify the cellar every cycle and drive RH into the 30s. That's why real cellar units from WhisperKOOL, Wine Guardian, CellarPro, and Breezaire include humidity management as a core design feature, not an afterthought."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My cellar temperature is fluctuating — what's wrong?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Fluctuation usually points to one of four places. A refrigerant charge that's low from a slow leak — common in older split systems. An evaporator fan that's drawing weak current and not circulating air properly. A TXV (thermostatic expansion valve) that's drifted or stuck. Or a control board with a failing temperature probe, which can cause the unit to cycle on incorrect readings. On ducted systems, an air flow restriction — a dirty filter, a collapsed flex duct — causes the same symptom. We diagnose by measuring superheat, subcooling, amp draw, and return-air temperature rather than guessing."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you work on WhisperKOOL, Wine Guardian, and CellarPro units?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — those three brands plus Breezaire and KoolR are the cellar cooling systems we service most often in LA. We carry evaporator fan motors, control boards, and condensate pumps for the common models (WhisperKOOL Platinum and 8000 series, Wine Guardian D025 through D088, CellarPro 1800 through 8200 series, Breezaire WKCE and WKL). Refrigerant service — leak detection, recovery, recharge — is handled in-house with EPA-certified technicians. For proprietary parts like CellarPro VSi control boards, we order direct from the manufacturer and confirm lead time before scheduling."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is my problem the equipment or the cellar envelope?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "This is the most important question on a cellar call, and most repair companies skip it. If a cooling unit is running continuously but the room won't hold temperature, the equipment may be fine — the envelope may be failing. We check for missing or compromised 6-mil poly vapor barrier on the warm side, insulation gaps, door seal failure, and condensation inside walls (a sign the vapor barrier is missing and moisture is migrating into the framing). A cellar where the equipment is working correctly but the room drifts needs envelope work, not a bigger cooling unit. We'll tell you honestly which one it is."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can you repair a ducted split wine cellar system?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Ducted split systems — where the condensing unit lives in a mechanical room or outside, and the evaporator sits in the cellar with copper line sets connecting them — are our specialty in larger Malibu and Beverly Hills cellars. We service the refrigerant circuit (leak detection, recovery, recharge of R-404A, R-134a, or R-513A), the evaporator and blower assembly, the line set and insulation, the condensate drain and pump, and the controls. LA's seasonal temperature swing stresses these systems in ways a constant-climate installation doesn't — we understand the failure modes specific to this region."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does the 90-day warranty cover on wine cellar repairs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every wine cellar repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge — in writing before we leave. For refrigerant work, the warranty covers the repair and the charge, not a pre-existing leak elsewhere in the system that we disclosed at the time of service."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

